Encryption key operations on the read path

        
    

Making copies fast
This setup really shines in one of our most common workflows: when someone adds a shared file or folder to their own Dropbox. Before, that kind of cross-team copy would require re-encrypting every block in the file. For large files‚Äîsome with hundreds of thousands of blocks‚Äîthat would take ages.
With this new model, Dropbox only needs to make a re-encrypted copy of the source namespace‚Äôs NEK to grant access. While it‚Äôs a huge performance win, it‚Äôs not a long-term solution‚Äîthe recipient shouldn‚Äôt hold onto the original team‚Äôs NEK forever. So, behind the scenes, Dropbox runs background processes that slowly re-encrypt every block with the recipient‚Äôs keys. This way, we return to a clean, steady state without making users wait for all that processing upfront. It also turns out this approach aligns really well with our existing data locality architecture, which meant we could reuse a lot of the foundational setup.



 Additional implementation considerations




Key caching
Even though we added a new encryption tier, overall system load is lower because we no longer need to hit the top-level key for every block. But we still need to avoid overwhelming AWS KMS. That‚Äôs why we cache NEKs in memory for a short period. Since file operations tend to happen in bursts‚Äîlike uploading or syncing multiple files at once‚Äîthis cache is very effective in cutting down on repeated KMS calls.


    
        
            
    

        

        
        
        

        
        
        

        
        

        
